<subSubSection id="940767BD9E802B075A55353209E80BBF" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4BB70FBF9FD1890A9D6383CF16045135" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<pageBreakToken id="81EA0CC71240EFE0369E2D2D15D2D6D7" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC6E88BC39E664AA31E1C03F1C448F9" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="1713E29D72560D87B918D4602B52563E" family="Commelinaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. spectabilis" order="Commelinales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species" species="spectabilis">
<emphasis id="01E3F01CC84F77CB92274EC30D45CACF" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">S. spectabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
due to its vining habit, distichously-alternate leaves, blades asymmetric at base, main florescence a many-branched thyrse, with alternate cincinni, flowers bisexual or staminate, zygomorphic, stamens unequal, curved upwards and sigmoid filaments. It can be differentiated from by its chartaceous and sparsely velutine leaves, inflorescences axillary in the primary branches or terminal in the secondary branches, and petals white with glabrous margins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
